stickerText: 40% of Indigenous people who contract HIV are women.
Despite this high rate of infection among Indigenous women, they have been able to significantly limit HIV transmission to their babies.
Between 1984 & 2010, only three babies were born with HIV.
When a woman is on proper HIV medication, the chance of passing HIV to her baby through birth is extremely low.
However, the chance of transmitting HIV to a baby through breastfeeding is much higher.
The best way to protect yourself & your baby is to know your status.
Visit sexfluent.ca to learn more about the different HIV testing options available to you.

stickerText: Why does HIV disportionately affect Indigenous communities & how does this relate to reconciliation?
In Canada, our healthcare system has a mainstream approach to HIV which often doesn’t properly consider spiritual, cultural, mental & physical wellbeing of Indigenous people
Or the geographic barriers to healthcare many Indigenous people face.
In a study conducted within northern Indigenous community:
14% reported they had unmet healthcare needs..
In so many Indigenous communities, there is very little access to sexual health clinics & the stigma associated with getting tested for HIV at a regular healthcare clinic is dangerously overpowering.
History has shown us that colonizers who came into Indigenous communities & tell us how healthcare should operate has not worked in the past, & it will not work now.
Knowing your HIV status is a necessary first step, but what happens next?
No one should have to travel hundreds of miles to access the healthcare services they need to survive.
Each group involved needs to be at the decision making table.
We need to increase the cultural competency for non-Indigenous healthcare workers
We need to increase the Indigenous healthcare workforce.
Visit sexfluent.ca for resources on HIV

stickerText: Between 1800s to 1996, residential schools were put in place to force Indigenous children from their homes.
If the parents didn’t comply, there were serious consequences.
They were forced to assimilate into modern society.
Not allowed to practice culture or talk in their own languages.
Some children never made it home.
These “schools” were funded by the government.
Who’s going to be held accountable?

stickerText: Im pretty sure every Canadian knows this blanket..
But I want to come on here & educate those who dont.
They are called the Hudsons Bay Company blankets
The HBC came down the Hudsons Bay
When the HBC came along, they wanted to trade with the Natives of Canada
Thats when ALLL the fur trade happened..
There was one time the HBC came back from Europe
& they traded these blankets with the Natives
These blankets were infected with Small Pox🛑
Now its very clear that they wanted to get rid of us..
